entry.title: Outline
entry.content:
1. Studying the trend of gender proportion in STEM diciplines by line charts
  2. Studying the trend of gender proportion in Liberal Arts diciplines by line charts
  3. Comparing the trend of gender proportion betweem STEM, Liberal Arts, and the other diciplines.
  4. Generating a interactive plot to observe gender proportions betweem STEM, Liberal Arts, and the other diciplines across years.
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
plt.style.use("fivethirtyeight")
%matplotlib inline

The Department of Education Statistics releases a data set annually containing the percentage of bachelor's degrees granted to women from 1970 to 2012. The data set is broken up into 17 categories of degrees, with each column as a separate category.

women_degrees = pd.read_csv('percent-bachelors-degrees-women-usa.csv')

# two colors in Color Blind 10 palette
cb_dark_blue = (0/255,107/255,164/255) 
cb_orange = (255/255, 128/255, 14/255)

women_degrees.head()
Year Agriculture Architecture Art and Performance Biology Business Communications and Journalism Computer Science Education Engineering English Foreign Languages Health Professions Math and Statistics Physical Sciences Psychology Public Administration Social Sciences and History

4 1974 14.074623 17.444688 61.9 32.996183 16.204850 40.5 18.9 73.336811 2.2 62.413412 75.3 77.9 41.8 18.2 52.6 66.1 37.3

       'Business', 'Communications and Journalism', 'Computer Science',
       'Education', 'Engineering', 'English', 'Foreign Languages',
       'Health Professions', 'Math and Statistics', 'Physical Sciences',
       'Psychology', 'Public Administration', 'Social Sciences and History'],

(42, 18)
stem_cats = ['Psychology', 'Biology', 'Math and Statistics', 
             'Physical Sciences', 'Computer Science', 
             'Engineering']

lib_arts_cats = ['Foreign Languages', 'English', 
                 'Communications and Journalism', 
                 'Art and Performance', 
                 'Social Sciences and History']

other_cats = ['Health Professions', 'Public Administration', 
              'Education', 'Agriculture',
              'Business', 'Architecture']

Comparing across STEM (Science, Technology, Engineering, Mathematics) 

fig, axis = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=3,
                         figsize=(30, 15))
fig.suptitle("Proportions of gender between STEM disciplines", 
             fontsize=35, y=1.05)

for subject, ax in zip(stem_cats, axis.flat):
    #plot the line
    ax.plot(women_degrees['Year'], women_degrees[subject], 
            c=cb_orange, label='Women', linewidth=3)
    ax.plot(women_degrees['Year'], 100-women_degrees[subject], 
            c=cb_dark_blue, label='Men', linewidth=3)
    
    # set graph attriibutes
    ax.set_xlim(1968, 2011)
    ax.set_ylim(0,100)
    ax.set_title(subject, fontsize=25)
    ax.tick_params(bottom="off", top="off", 
                   left="off", right="off")
    ax.set_ylabel("percent (%)", size=20)
    ax.set_xlabel("year", size=20)
    
    # add the text to represent the line label 
    # on the first and last graphs
    if  subject == "Psychology":
        ax.text(2005, 85, 'Women', size=20)
        ax.text(2002, 14, 'Men', size=20)
    elif subject == "Physical Sciences":
        ax.text(2005, 64, 'Men', size=20)
        ax.text(2005, 33, 'Women', size=20)
        
plt.tight_layout(pad=1.2)

Comparing across liberal arts 

fig, axis = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=3,
                         figsize=(30, 15))
fig.suptitle("Proportions of gender between liberal arts disciplines", 
             fontsize=35, y=1.05)

for subject, ax in zip(lib_arts_cats, axis.flat):
    
    #plot the line
    ax.plot(women_degrees['Year'], women_degrees[subject], 
            c=cb_orange, label='Women', linewidth=3)
    ax.plot(women_degrees['Year'], 100-women_degrees[subject], 
            c=cb_dark_blue, label='Men', linewidth=3)
    
    #remove all the spines
    ax.spines["right"].set_visible(False)    
    ax.spines["left"].set_visible(False)
    ax.spines["top"].set_visible(False)    
    ax.spines["bottom"].set_visible(False)
    
    # set graph attriibutes
    ax.set_xlim(1968, 2011)
    ax.set_ylim(0,100)
    ax.set_title(subject, fontsize=25)
    ax.tick_params(bottom="off", top="off", 
                   left="off", right="off")
    ax.set_ylabel("percent (%)", size=20)
    ax.set_xlabel("year", size=20)
    
    # add the text to represent the line label 
    # on the first and last graphs
    if subject == "Foreign Languages":
        ax.text(2005, 85, 'Women', size=18)
        ax.text(2002, 14, 'Men', size=18)
    elif subject == "Art and Performance":
        ax.text(2005, 64, 'Men', size=18)
        ax.text(2005, 33, 'Women', size=18)

axis[1][2].set_axis_off()
plt.tight_layout(pad=1.2)

Comparing across all degree categories 

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(25,45))
plt.suptitle("Proportion trends between disciplines (STEM, Liberal Art, Others)", x=.5, y=1.02, size=30)

# Generate first column (stem)
for i in range(1,19,3):
    cat_index = int((i-1)/3)
    # plot a 6 by 3 figure
    ax = fig.add_subplot(6,3,i)
    ax.plot(women_degrees['Year'], women_degrees[stem_cats[cat_index]], 
            c=cb_orange, label='Women', linewidth=3)
    ax.plot(women_degrees['Year'], 100-women_degrees[stem_cats[cat_index]], 
            c=cb_dark_blue, label='Men', linewidth=3)
    
    # set graph attributes
    ax.set_xlim(1968, 2011)
    ax.set_ylim(0,100)
    ax.set_title(stem_cats[cat_index], size=25)
    ax.tick_params(bottom="off", top="off", 
                   left="off", right="off")
    ax.set_ylabel("percent (%)", size=20)
    ax.set_xlabel("year", size=20)
    plt.legend(prop={'size': 15})
    
    if cat_index == 0:
        ax.text(2003, 80, 'Women', size=15)
        ax.text(2005, 15, 'Men', size=15)
        ax.get_legend().remove()
    elif cat_index == 5:
        ax.text(2005, 85, 'Men', size=15)
        ax.text(2003, 10, 'Women', size=15)
        ax.get_legend().remove()

# Generate second column (liberal art)
for i in range(2,15,3):
    cat_index = int((i-1)/3)
    ax = fig.add_subplot(6,3,i)
    ax.plot(women_degrees['Year'], women_degrees[lib_arts_cats[cat_index]], 
            c=cb_orange, label='Women', linewidth=3)
    ax.plot(women_degrees['Year'], 100-women_degrees[lib_arts_cats[cat_index]], 
            c=cb_dark_blue, label='Men', linewidth=3)
    
    ax.set_xlim(1968, 2011)
    ax.set_ylim(0,100)
    ax.set_title(lib_arts_cats[cat_index], size=25)
    ax.tick_params(bottom="off", top="off", 
                   left="off", right="off")
    ax.set_ylabel("percent (%)", size=20)
    ax.set_xlabel("year", size=20)
    plt.legend(prop={'size': 15})
    
    if cat_index == 0:
        ax.text(2003, 75, 'Women', size=15)
        ax.text(2005, 23, 'Men', size=15)
        ax.get_legend().remove()
    elif cat_index == 4:
        ax.text(1973, 30, 'Women', size=15)
        ax.text(1973, 70, 'Men', size=15)
        ax.get_legend().remove()
        
# Generate third column (other)
for i in range(3,19,3):
    cat_index = int((i-1)/3)
    ax = fig.add_subplot(6,3,i)
    ax.plot(women_degrees['Year'], women_degrees[other_cats[cat_index]], 
            c=cb_orange, label='Women', linewidth=3)
    ax.plot(women_degrees['Year'], 100-women_degrees[other_cats[cat_index]], 
            c=cb_dark_blue, label='Men', linewidth=3)

    ax.set_xlim(1968, 2011)
    ax.set_ylim(0,100)
    ax.set_title(other_cats[cat_index], size=25)
    ax.tick_params(bottom="off", top="off", 
                   left="off", right="off")
    ax.set_ylabel("percent (%)", size=20)
    ax.set_xlabel("year", size=20)
    plt.legend(prop={'size': 15})
    
    if cat_index == 0:
        ax.text(2003, 90, 'Women', size=15)
        ax.text(2005, 8, 'Men', size=15)
        ax.get_legend().remove()
    elif cat_index == 5:
        ax.text(2005, 60, 'Men', size=15)
        ax.text(2003, 36, 'Women', size=15)
        ax.get_legend().remove()

from bokeh.io import show, push_notebook
from bokeh.plotting import figure

from ipywidgets import interact

year=1970

source1 = tidy_data[(tidy_data["Type"] == "STEM") & (tidy_data["Year"] == year)]
s = figure(y_range=source1["Discipline"], plot_height=250, 
           plot_width=800, title="STEM")

             source=source1, color=["pink", "lightblue"])

source2 = tidy_data[(tidy_data["Type"] == "Liberal Arts") & (tidy_data["Year"] == year)]

           plot_width=800, title="Liberal Arts")

                  source=source2, color=["pink", "lightblue"])

o = figure(y_range=source3["Discipline"], plot_height=250,
           plot_width=800, title="Others")
og = o.hbar_stack(stackers=["Female proportion", "Male proportion"], y="Discipline", height=0.8, 
             source=source3, color=["pink", "lightblue"])

def update(year, subjects):
    sg[0].data_source.data = dict(tidy_data[(tidy_data["Type"] == "STEM") & (tidy_data["Year"] == year)])
    sg[1].data_source.data = dict(tidy_data[(tidy_data["Type"] == "STEM") & (tidy_data["Year"] == year)])
    
    lg[0].data_source.data = dict(tidy_data[(tidy_data["Type"] == "Liberal Arts") & (tidy_data["Year"] == year)])
    lg[1].data_source.data = dict(tidy_data[(tidy_data["Type"] == "Liberal Arts") & (tidy_data["Year"] == year)])
    
    og[0].data_source.data = dict(tidy_data[(tidy_data["Type"] == "Others") & (tidy_data["Year"] == year)])
    og[1].data_source.data = dict(tidy_data[(tidy_data["Type"] == "Others") & (tidy_data["Year"] == year)])
    if subjects == "STEM":
        show(s, notebook_handle=True)
    elif subjects == "Liberal Arts":
        show(l)
    elif subjects == "Others":
        show(o)
    push_notebook()

interact(update, year=(1970, 2011), subjects=["STEM", "Liberal Arts", "Others"]);

entry.title: Interactive Visualization of Change in Female College Major Percentage with Altair

link.title: Interactive Visualization of Change in Female College Major Percentage with Altair

entry.content:
In this project, I make some simple interactive graphs to show annual changes in proportions of female college major in different disciplines. The data I used is obtained from The Department of Education Statistics. It contains the proportions of female college majors in 17 disciplines in each year from 1970 to 2011. To make these analysis more easily understood, I will split these disciplines into three groups: STEM, Liberal Arts and the others, and plot each disciplines in these three groups.

I use Python for this project. The programming tool I used for visualizing the data is Altair, a declarative statistical visualization library for Python. You can find the source code on GitHub.

This project consists of three parts:

  • a preview of our data to gain a brief understanding
  • preprocessing to make the data easier to be visualized
  • making interactive graphs to discovery information

A preview of the data 

import pandas as pd

women_degrees = pd.read_csv('percent-bachelors-degrees-women-usa.csv')
women_degrees.iloc[:, :8].head()

entry.title: Whats the difference between a metric and a loss?

link.title: Whats the difference between a metric and a loss?

entry.content:
In machine learning, there are usually two values used to evaluate our model: a metric and a loss. For instance, if we are doing a binary classification task, our metric may be the accuracy and our loss would be the cross-entroy. They both show how good our model performs. However, why do we need both rather than just use one of them? Furthermore, what's the difference between them?

The short answer is that the metric is for human while the loss is for your model.

Based on the metric, machine learning paritioners such as data scientis and researchers assess a machine learning model. On the assessment, ML paritioners make decisions to address their problems or achieve their business goals. For example , say a data scientist aims to build a spam classifier to distinguish normal email from spam with 95% accuracy. First, the data scientist bulid a logistic regression model with 90% accruay. Apparently, this result doesn't meet his business goal, so he tries to build another model. After training a random forest model, he get a classifier with 97% accuracy, which goes beyond his goal. Since the goal is met, the data scientist decides to integrate this model into his data product. ML partitioners use the metric to tell whether their model is good enough.

On the other hand, a loss indicates in what direction your model should improve. The difference between machine learning and traditinal programming is how they get the ability to solve a problem. Traditional programs solve problems by following exact instructions given by prgrammers. On the contrary, a machine learning models learn that by taking into some examples (data) and discovery the underlying patterns. How does a machine learning model do that? Most ML models learn from a gradient-based method. Here's how a gradient-based method (be specifically, a gradient descent method in supervised learning context) works:

  1. A model takes into data and makes predictions.
  2. Compute a loss based on the predictions and the true data.
  3. Compute the gradients of the loss with respect to parameters of the model.
  4. Updating these parameters based on these gradients.

The gradient of the loss helps our model to get better and better. The reason why we need a loss is that it is sensitive enough to small changes so our model can improve. More precisely, the gradient of the loss should vary if our parameters change slighly. In our spam classification example, accuracy is obviously not suitable for being a loss since it only changes when some examples are classified differently. The cross-entrpy is relatively smoother and so it is a good candidate for a loss. However, a metric do not have to be different from a loss. A metric can be a loss as long as it is sensitive enough. For instance, in a regression setting, MSE (mean squared error) can be both a metric and a loss.

In summary, a metric helps ML partitioners to evaluate their models and a loss faciliates the learning process of a ML model.

entry.title: Analyzing Sharing Bikes Usage Trends
entry.content:
Introduction

In this project I ask questions about how people use bike-sharing system. All these questions will be answered by graphs generating from data.

The data I used contains information about how people use sharing bike hourly in Washington, D.C. from 2011 to 2012. It is obtained from UCI machine learning repository originating from Capital Bikeshire. You can find the Jupyter Notebook of this project in this github repository.

The project consists of two parts. In first part I modifiy the dataset to make it easier to be analyzed including changing variable names and modifying variable values. I start my analysis in the second part where I ask questions on sharing bike usage from several perspectives such as in different time or weather, or if the user is registered. Let's get started.

Precprocessing

The raw data is often not very readable and understandable, so we should first have a glimpse at our data, understand how it looks like, and make a few modifications before we delve into it.

(Here are some programming settings. You can check them by hitting the show code button.)

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
plt.style.use("fivethirtyeight")
%matplotlib inline

# setting params
params = {'legend.fontsize': 'large',
          'figure.figsize': (20, 10),
          'figure.dpi': 120,
          'axes.labelsize': 'x-large',
          'axes.titlesize':'x-large',
          'xtick.labelsize':'x-large',
          'ytick.labelsize':'x-large'}

plt.rcParams.update(params)
pd.options.display.max_colwidth = 800

from IPython.display import display, HTML

Having a brief look at our data

Let's load the data into our notebook and take a look at it.

hour_df = pd.read_csv("data/hour.csv")
hour_df.head().iloc[:,:10]

We load the data from the file hour.csv, which contains the bike usage records at each hour between years 2011 and 2012. The table above tells us that our data contains 17379 data points and 17 variables with no missing value. Most variable names are self-explanatory but some are confusing such as dtedat. We must find the meanings of these confusing variables by checking the documentation of the data, and rename them accordingly. Furthermore, some variables are encoded in a way that's not easy to be understood by human. For example, values of weekday range from 0 to 6 representing days from Sunday to Saturday respectively. To understand the data better, we also need to take care of this issue.

Modifying the data set

We first change the names of variables by making a name mapping and passing it into the rename method of DataFrame.

variables_mapping = {"instant":"index",
                     "dteday":"datetime",
                     "mnth":"month",
                     "holiday":"is_holiday",
                     "weekday":"day",
                     "workingday":"is_workingday",
                     "weathersit":"weather_condition",
                     "temp":"temperature",
                     "atemp": "feeling temperature",
                     "hum":"humidity",
                     "yr":"year",
                     "hr":"hour",
                     "cnt":"count"}
hour_df = hour_df.rename(columns=variables_mapping)
hour_df.columns

Index(['index', 'datetime', 'season', 'year', 'month', 'hour', 'is_holiday',
       'day', 'is_workingday', 'weather_condition', 'temperature',
       'feeling temperature', 'humidity', 'windspeed', 'casual', 'registered',
       'count'],
      dtype='object')

Next, we convert to more understanable names the values of these 4 variables: day, month, season and year.

day_mapping = {0:"Sunday", 1:"Monday",
                   2:"Tuesday", 3:"Wednesday",
                   4:"Thursday", 5:"Friday",
                   6:"Saturday"}
season_mapping = {1:"winter", 2:"spring", 
                  3:"summer", 4:"fall"}
month_mapping = {1:"Jan", 2:"Feb", 3:"Mar", 4:"Apr",
                 5:"May", 6:"Jun", 7:"Jul", 8:"Aug",
                 9:"Sep", 10:"Oct", 11:"Nov", 12:"Dec"}
year_mapping = {0:"2011", 1:"2012"}

map_vars = ["day", "month", "season", "year"]
mappings = [day_mapping, month_mapping, 
            season_mapping, year_mapping]

for var, mapping in zip(map_vars, mappings):
    hour_df[var] = hour_df[var].map(mapping)

Let's see the unique values of these 4 variables:

for var in map_vars:
    print(var + ":")
    print(hour_df[var].unique())
    print()

day:
['Saturday' 'Sunday' 'Monday' 'Tuesday' 'Wednesday' 'Thursday' 'Friday']

month:
['Jan' 'Feb' 'Mar' 'Apr' 'May' 'Jun' 'Jul' 'Aug' 'Sep' 'Oct' 'Nov' 'Dec']

season:
['winter' 'spring' 'summer' 'fall']

year:
['2011' '2012']

Now it's much easier to understand what each variable stands for and what the values of each variable means. (However, if my goal is to build a machine learning model, I would not transfer these variable values since machine learning model only takes into numerical values as input.) After we complete these modifications, we can start analyzing the data.

Visualize Bike Usage Trends

I will analyze the data from three aspects:

  • What time do people use sharing bike? How do people use bikes at each hour, on each day, or in each month?
  • In what weather do people use sharing bike? Would people like to use sharing bike even when it's raining?
  • What is the difference of usage pattern between registered users and casual ones?

All these questions would be answered with graphs.

(Here's a helper function to make my code more concise.)

def get_grouped_average(groups, selected_var=["count"]):
    group_df = hour_df.groupby(groups).mean()[selected_var]
    return group_df.reset_index()

What time would people use sharing bike?

First, let's take a look at how people use sharing bike at each hour in a day.

average_hourly = get_grouped_average(["hour"])

sns.pointplot(x="hour", y="count", data=average_hourly)
plt.ylabel("Average count")
plt.title("Average bike usage in each hour", size=20);

I group the data by hour, compute the average bike usage of each hour, and plot the graph above. From the graph, we can see two usage peaks in a day, from 6 a.m. to 9 a.m and from 4 p.m. to 7 p.m. These two time periods are when people go to work and get home from work, so it seems that people use sharing bikes for transportation to and from work. To justify this further, let's look into how people use sharing bikes on different days in a week.

# hourly distribution between different weekdays
data_day = get_grouped_average(["hour", "day"])

# plotting
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
sns.pointplot(data=data_day, x="hour", 
              y="count", hue="day", ax=ax)
plt.ylabel("Average count")
plt.title("Average usage between different hours and days", size=20);

The usage patterns on Saturday and Sunday are substantially different from the ones on weekdays. Two peaks appearing on weekdays don't exist on weekend and more people use sharing bike from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. on weekend than on weekdays. This distinction can be observed more clearly if we investigate the is_workingday variable.

data_working = get_grouped_average(["hour", "is_workingday"])

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
sns.pointplot(x="hour", y="count", 
              hue="is_workingday", 
              data=data_working, ax=ax)
plt.title("Average bike usage on working day", size=20)
plt.ylabel("Average usage");
#plt.savefig("bike_shire.png", dpi=80);

The is_workingday variable indicates if a day is a working day; the variable equals 1 if a day is a working day and 0 if it's a holiday. As a result, it is comfirmed from this figure that people have two distinct bike usage patterns: on working days and on holidays.

Next let's see the monthly usage of sharing bikes.

hour_df.groupby(["month"])["count"].describe()

As shown in the graph, people use sharing bikes more frequently in the period from May to September in a year. What's the possible explanation for this phenonmenon? I have an intuition that the monthly difference is due to the weather, so I would study how people use sharing bikes in different weather in the next section.

In what weather would people use sharing bike?

In this part, I study variables related to the weather: temperature, humidity, windspeed, and weather condition. The first three variables are numerical and the last one is categorical. I will first look into these three numerical ones and the categorical one later.

I believe weather has influence on the frequency of people using sharing bike. Intuitively, people ride bikes more on warmer days and less on raining or windy days. Let's see if tha data tell the same story.

weather_variables = ["temperature", "humidity",
                     "windspeed", "count"]
weather_monthly = get_grouped_average(["month"], weather_variables)

fig, axes = plt.subplots(2,2)
for var, ax in zip(weather_variables, axes.flatten()):
    sns.barplot(x="month", y=var, data=weather_monthly, 
                order=month_order, ax=ax)
    ax.set_xlabel(None);

It seems that the temperature have a strong impact on bike usage since it shows a very similar pattern with count. In contrast, the windspeed and humidity is not as mush correlated with count as the temperature does. To have a more detailed observation, we can take a look at the correlations.

corr_matrix = hour_df[weather_variables].corr().round(3)

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6), dpi=100)
sns.heatmap(corr_matrix, vmin=-1, vmax=1,
            square=True, annot=True, cmap="Blues");

The correlation between count and temperature is around 0.41, which tells us that people use sharing bike more when the weather is warmer. On the contrary, count and humidity are negatively correlated. The humidity would be high if it is raining outside and people won't use sharing bike when it's raining, so that might explain why the correlation between count and humidity is negative.

Let's take a look at the weather_condition:

hour_df['weather_condition'].unique()

array([1, 2, 3, 4])

This variable has 4 unique values indicating different weather conditions:

  • 1: Clear, Few clouds, Partly cloudy, or Partly cloudy
  • 2: Mist + Cloudy, Mist + Broken clouds, Mist + Few clouds, or Mist
  • 3: Light Snow, Light Rain + Thunderstorm + Scattered clouds, or Light Rain + Scattered clouds
  • 4: Heavy Rain + Ice Pallets + Thunderstorm + Mist, or Snow + Fog

The bigger the value is, the worse the weather is. People would use sharing bikes more when it is in good whether but would use less when it's in bad weather. Thus, count may be larger when weather_condition is equal to 1 and, conversely, smaller when weather_conditoin is 4. Let's see if it is so.

hour_df.groupby("weather_condition")["count"].describe().T

You can easily tell from the table that people use sharing bikes much less frequent in extreme weather.

Registered or not?

There are two kinds of users in our dataset: registered and casual. How do registered users behave differently from causal users?

hour_df[["registered", "casual"]].describe()

From the table above, registered users use sharing bike much more frequently than casual ones. Next, we investigate how they behave differently in each hour and each day in a week.

register_hourly = get_grouped_average(["hour"], ["registered", "casual"])

fig, ax = plt.subplots(2,1)

sns.pointplot(x='hour', y="registered",
              data=register_hourly, label="registered",
              ax=ax[0])
ax[0].set_ylabel("registered", size=20)
ax[0].set_xlabel(None)
sns.pointplot(x='hour', y="casual", color="orange",
              data=register_hourly, label="registered",
              ax=ax[1])
ax[1].set_ylabel("casual", size=20)
plt.tight_layout();


register_day = get_grouped_average(["day"], ["registered", "casual"])
day_order = ["Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday",
             "Friday", "Saturday","Sunday"]

fig, ax=plt.subplots(2,1, figsize=(20, 15))
sns.barplot(x="day", y="registered", 
            data=register_day, order=day_order,
            ax=ax[0])
ax[0].set_xlabel(None)
sns.barplot(x="day", y="casual", 
            data=register_day, order=day_order,
            ax=ax[1]);

From graphs above, it is apperant that people who use sharing bike to go to work register as a member more than people who do not.

Summary

From this analysis, we can know three charateristics about how people use sharing bikes:

  1. Most people use sharing bikes to go to and get back from work.
  2. People use sharing bikes less frequently in bad weather (e.g. heavy rain, or strong wind).
  3. Most registered user use sharing bikes for work probably because they use sharing bikes regularly.

In order to get more information from the data, we might consider training a machine learning model which takes count as the dependent variable and the others as independent variables. By doing that, we can understand which variables have influence on bike usage and how these variables affect bike usage.

import os

              "20030228_spam_2.tar.bz2"]
store_path = os.path.join("data")

def fetch_data(root_url=download_root, file_names=file_names,
               store_path=store_path):
    
    # make directory storing emails
    os.makedirs(store_path, exist_ok=True)
    
    # download files 
    for file in file_names:
        file_url = os.path.join(download_root, file)
        path = os.path.join(store_path, file)
        urllib.request.urlretrieve(file_url, path)
    
    # extract emails
    for file in file_names:
        path = os.path.join(store_path, file)
        with tarfile.open(path, 'r') as f:
            f.extractall(path=store_path)

    names = [name for name in sorted(os.listdir(ham_path)) if len(name) > 20]
    ham_names[ham] = names
    
spam_names = {}
for spam in email_folders[3:]:
    spam_path = os.path.join(store_path, spam)
    names = [name for name in sorted(os.listdir(spam_path)) if len(name) > 20]
    spam_names[spam] = names

# parse emails
import email
import email.policy

def load_email(directory, filename, spam_path=store_path):
    path = os.path.join(spam_path, directory)
    with open(os.path.join(path, filename), "rb") as f:
        return email.parser.BytesParser(policy=email.policy.default).parse(f)
hams = []
for ham in email_folders[:3]:
    emails = [load_email(ham, filename=name) for name in ham_names[ham]]
    hams.extend(emails)
spams = []
for spam in email_folders[3:]:
    emails = [load_email(spam, filename=name) for name in spam_names[spam]]
    spams.extend(emails)

from collections import Counter 

def get_email_structure(email):
    if isinstance(email, str):
        return email
    payload = email.get_payload()
    if isinstance(payload, list):
        return "multipart({})".format(", ".join([
            get_email_structure(sub_email)
            for sub_email in payload
        ]))
    else:
        return email.get_content_type()

def structure_counter(emails):
    structures = [get_email_structure(email) for email in emails]

from bs4 import BeautifulSoup

def html_to_plain_text(html):
    soup = BeautifulSoup(html, "lxml")
    strings = ""
    for i in soup.find_all():
        if i.string:
            strings += i.string + "\n"
    return strings

Turn email to plain text

def email_to_text(email):
    html = None
    for part in email.walk():
        ctype = part.get_content_type()
        if not ctype in ("text/plain", "text/html"):
            continue
        try:
            content = part.get_content()
        except: # in case of encoding issues
            content = str(part.get_payload())
        if ctype == "text/plain":
            return content
        else:
            html = content
    if html:
        return html_to_plain_text(html)

from sklearn.base import BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin

class EmailToTokenizedStemmed(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    def __init__(self, strip_headers=True, lower_case=True, remove_punctuation=True,
                 replace_urls=True, replace_numbers=True, stemming=True):
        self.strip_headers = strip_headers
        self.lower_case = lower_case
        self.remove_punctuation = remove_punctuation
        self.replace_urls = replace_urls
        self.replace_numbers = replace_numbers
        self.stemming = stemming
        
    def fit(self, X, y=None):
        return self
    
    def transform(self, X, y=None):
        X_transformed = []
        for email in X:
            text = email_to_text(email) or ""
            if self.lower_case:
                text = text.lower()
            if self.replace_urls:
                url_pattern = 'http[s]?://(?:[a-zA-Z]|[0-9]|[$-_@.&+]|[!*\(\),]|(?:%[0-9a-fA-F][0-9a-fA-F]))+'
                text = re.sub(url_pattern, "URL", text)
            if self.replace_numbers:
                text = re.sub(r'\d+(?:\.\d*(?:[eE]\d+))?', 'NUMBER', text)
            if self.remove_punctuation:
                text = re.sub(r'[^a-zA-Z0-9]+', ' ', text, flags=re.M)
            text = word_tokenize(text)
            text = stemming_email(text)
            X_transformed.append(text)
        return np.array(X_transformed)

Comparing performance of models using ROC curve and AUC 

from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, roc_auc_score

def plot_roc_curve(models_names=models_names, models=models):
    
    plt.figure(dpi=120)
    for name in models_names:
        if name == "SVM":
            y_score = models[name].decision_function(X_test_processed)
            fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_score)
            auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_score)
            label = name + f"({auc:.4f})"
            plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label=label)
        else:
            y_score = models[name].predict_proba(X_test_processed)[:,1]
            fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, y_score)
            auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, y_score)
            label = name + f"({auc:.4f})"
            plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label=label)
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0,1], "b--")
    plt.xlim(-0.01, 1.02)
    plt.ylim(-0.01, 1.02)
    plt.legend(title="Model (AUC score)",loc=(1.01, 0.4))

plot_roc_curve()
